<ArticleLayout
  title="Nursery Essentials for Australian Homes"
  description="A guide to the nursery basics Australian families may need for sleep, feeding, changing, storage and comfort."
  category="Nursery & Kids"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="7 minute read"
  image="/images/Nursery-kids.webp"
  imageAlt="A tidy nursery room with timber furniture, soft lighting and practical baby storage"
>
  <p>
    A nursery shopping list can grow faster than the room. A baby still needs a safe place to
    sleep, somewhere to be changed, clothes, feeding supplies and a few care items within reach.
    The rest can develop after the household knows which routines need help.
  </p>
  <p>
    The room does not have to be large or expensive. It has to work during an overnight change,
    leave clear space to move and suit the climate and layout of the home. In many families, the
    first “nursery” is a safe sleep space in the parent or caregiver's room and a portable change
    caddy.
  </p>

  <h2>The nursery basics at a glance</h2>
  <ComparisonTable rows={comparisonRows} caption="Nursery essentials comparison" />

  <h2>Set up the safe sleep space first</h2>
  <p>
    Choose a cot, bassinet or bedside sleeper that meets applicable Australian requirements and
    suits the baby's age, the product instructions and the room. Assemble it exactly as directed
    and use the mattress intended or specified for that product.
  </p>
  <p>
    Current Red Nose guidance says to place babies on their back to sleep, keep the face and head
    uncovered and use the baby's own safe sleep space with a safe mattress and bedding. It also
    recommends that this space be in the parent or caregiver's room for the first six months.
    Check the{" "}
    <a href="https://rednose.org.au/resources/safe-sleeping/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Red Nose safe sleeping guide</a>{" "}
    and the{" "}
    <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/about-us/our-campaigns/sleep-bub-safe" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC Sleep bub safe resources</a>{" "}
    when choosing and setting up the product.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep pillows, doonas, cot bumpers, toys and other loose soft items out of an infant's sleep
    space. Styling trends change; safe use must continue to follow current guidance and the
    product instructions.
  </p>

  <h2>Build the change area around supervision</h2>
  <p>
    A change setup needs a stable surface, supplies within reach and a clear plan for dirty nappies
    and clothing. It does not have to be a dedicated table, but any product or furniture used must
    be suitable for the task and set up according to its instructions.
  </p>
  <p>
    Never leave a baby unattended on a change surface. Keep one hand on the baby and take the baby
    with you if something is out of reach. The{" "}
    <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/keep-baby-safe/bathe-and-change-baby-safely" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC baby bathing and changing guidance</a>{" "}
    covers supervision and preparation.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep nappies, wipes, barrier cream and a clean change of clothes close enough to reach safely,
    while medicines, sanitiser, plastic bags and other hazardous or small items remain controlled.
    The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/nappy-change-station-checklist/">nappy change station checklist</a>{" "}
    works through surfaces, supplies, cleaning and room flow.
  </p>

  <h2>Store by the next care task</h2>
  <p>
    Baby clothes and supplies are small, but that does not mean each type needs its own organiser.
    Give the most accessible drawer or basket to the next size of clothing, nappies, wraps and
    cloths used every day. Put future sizes and occasional gear higher or deeper, provided they
    can be retrieved safely.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check furniture stability and follow any anchoring instructions. Keep storage away from the
    cot where a child could later reach, climb or pull items down. A room that works for a newborn
    will need to change as rolling, crawling and standing begin; the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/nursery-storage-small-rooms/">small nursery storage guide</a>{" "}
    plans for that shift.
  </p>

  <h2>Use the feeding place the household can sustain</h2>
  <p>
    Feeding may happen in the nursery, parents' room, living room or kitchen. Choose a chair or
    seat that is comfortable to enter and leave while holding the baby, then keep water, cloths
    and the relevant supplies nearby without crowding the floor.
  </p>
  <p>
    Bottle preparation, formula storage and cleaning need to follow health-professional and
    product guidance. They may be better organised in the kitchen than displayed in the nursery.
    Keep the room's setup focused on the part of the feeding routine that actually happens there.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan light for care, then darkness and privacy</h2>
  <p>
    The room needs enough light for dressing and checking the baby, plus a softer option for
    overnight care. Place lamps on stable surfaces, manage cords and keep equipment beyond the
    child's reach as mobility develops.
  </p>
  <p>
    Blockout curtains or blinds may help with glare, privacy and daytime light, but measure the
    window and watch how the room heats before buying. Blind and curtain cords must be secured in
    accordance with current safety requirements and kept away from cots and play areas.
  </p>

  <h2>Respond to the room's real temperature</h2>
  <p>
    Australian bedrooms range from hot, humid rooms to cold, draughty ones. Observe the nursery
    across the day and manage ventilation, heating or cooling in line with equipment instructions
    and current safe sleep advice. Avoid placing the sleep space in direct sun or immediately
    beside heaters, air-conditioner vents or other strong air flows.
  </p>
  <p>
    Buy sleepwear and layers for the room and season rather than building a large collection in
    advance. Red Nose guidance should remain the reference for safe bedding and temperature-related
    sleep decisions.
  </p>

  <h2>Buy clothing for the next laundry cycle</h2>
  <p>
    Start with a manageable set of bodysuits or singlets, simple outfits, sleepwear, bibs, feeding
    cloths, fitted sheets, towels and washcloths. The useful number depends on climate, washing
    frequency, drying space and how often changes are needed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid buying heavily in one size before knowing the baby's fit and growth. Washable clothing
    with simple fastenings generally makes repeated changes easier than outfits with complicated
    closures or special care.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep bathing gear portable and modest</h2>
  <p>
    Bathing supplies may include an appropriate baby bath or setup, towels, washcloths and the few
    products used during the wash. Keep everything within reach before water is involved and
    supervise continuously, following current ACCC guidance.
  </p>
  <p>
    A caddy can move dry supplies between nursery and bathroom, but wet cloths and towels need to
    dry before storage. Grooming tools such as nail files or clippers should be suitable, stored
    safely and used only when the caregiver feels confident.
  </p>

  <h2>Give dirty and clean linen separate routes</h2>
  <p>
    A hamper in or near the care area can contain clothes, sheets and cloths. Keep heavily soiled
    items controlled and follow product, garment and washing instructions. Fabrics and spare
    quantities should reflect the home's drying capacity, especially in humid or wet weather.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not store damp linen in drawers or closed tubs. The laundry route needs to end with items
    fully dry and easy to return, not with a second stockpile in the nursery.
  </p>

  <h2>Prioritise the first two weeks, not the finished room</h2>
  <p>The first version usually needs:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>A safe sleep product set up using current guidance.</li>
    <li>A stable, supervised changing position with reachable supplies.</li>
    <li>A manageable amount of clothing, sheets and feeding cloths.</li>
    <li>A hamper and a clear route for washing and drying.</li>
    <li>Simple storage for daily care items and the next clothing size.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A chair, monitor, bookshelf, blockout treatment or extra baskets can follow when the room and
    routine show a real need. Buying later also makes it easier to choose for the baby and home
    that actually exist rather than the nursery imagined before birth.
  </p>

  <FAQBlock items={faqs} />

  <h2>Keep safety guidance ahead of product trends</h2>
  <p>
    Nursery products, standards and advice can change. Recheck authoritative Australian guidance
    when buying second-hand, moving the sleep space, changing products or setting up the room for
    a new stage. A modest nursery that follows current guidance and supports overnight care is
    more useful than a finished-looking room full of untested extras.
  </p>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
</ArticleLayout>
